      "report": {
        "title": "NVIDIA GPU Architecture and AI Chip Lineup",
        "summary": "This report provides an overview of NVIDIA's GPU architecture for AI, including CUDA cores, Tensor Cores, and memory hierarchy. It also covers the current NVIDIA AI chip lineup, including A100, H100, RTX 30/40 series, and DGX systems, as well as the future roadmap of upcoming AI chip releases and architectural innovations.",
        "sections": [
          {
            "topic": "NVIDIA GPU Architecture for AI",
            "content": "NVIDIA GPUs have a compute hierarchy consisting of a GPU containing multiple Streaming Multiprocessors (SMs), each containing CUDA cores and Tensor Cores. The introduction of Tensor Cores in the NVIDIA Volta\u2122 GPU architecture accelerated matrix multiply and accumulate operations for machine learning and scientific applications. The NVIDIA H100 GPU includes 4th-generation Tensor Cores that support FP8 precision input, providing 2x the throughput of FP16. FP16 operations can be executed in either Tensor Cores or NVIDIA CUDA\u00ae cores, and INT8 operations can also be executed in either Tensor Cores or CUDA cores in the NVIDIA Turing\u2122 architecture.",
            "sources": [
              "https://docs.nvidia.com/deeplearning/performance/dl-performance-gpu-background/index.html",
              "https://www.nas.nasa.gov/hecc/support/kb/basics-on-nvidia-gpu-hardware-architecture_704.html"
            ]
          },
          {
            "topic": "Current NVIDIA AI Chip Lineup",
            "content": "The current NVIDIA AI chip lineup includes the A100 and H100 GPUs, which differ significantly in architecture and performance, with both supporting advanced features like Multi-Instance GPU (MIG) but optimized for different AI workloads. The NVIDIA B200 delivers inference at approximately $0.02 per million tokens at 55 TPS/user for GPT-OSS-120B using NVIDIA TensorRT\u2122-LLM, roughly 4.5x cheaper than H100. NVIDIA also introduced RTX PRO Servers powered by RTX PRO 6000 Blackwell Server Edition GPUs in May 2025, designed for enterprise AI factories to support multimodal AI inference and other workloads.",
            "sources": [
              "https://www.nvidia.com/en-us/data-center/h100/",
              "https://aimultiple.com/ai-chip-makers"
            ]
          },
          {
            "topic": "Future Roadmap",
            "content": "NVIDIA's roadmap includes the Blackwell architecture (2024) with chiplet GPU, FP4 precision, and NVLink 5 interconnects. The Blackwell Ultra (2025) will feature 288 GB of HBM3e memory. The Vera Rubin architecture (2026) will utilize HBM4 memory and 13 TB/s bandwidth. The Rubin Ultra (2027) will incorporate optical interconnects for improved data transfer. The Feynman architecture (2028) will introduce photonic rack-scale fabrics for distributed AI systems. NVIDIA's long-term goal is to transition GPUs into distributed AI fabrics rather than standalone accelerators.",
            "sources": [
              "https://community.hpe.com/t5/software-general/inside-nvidia-blackwell-the-gpu-architecture-redefining-the-age/td-p/7267262"
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
